    {
      "id": "9671d2eb713c1adf47e5392768c1156fbbffed13",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 09:26:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nAlex, it seems like there is a bug in the OFD locking if ofd_preprw_write() is using a read lock and updating attributes (e.g. size) that are affecting the read path?  I agree that we want to maximize concurrency in the write code, but either the read code has to handle this race correctly, or the locking needs to be exclusive between read and write.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "caea08451fe8cdcd34f6a86297a3aa132e8c3012",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 09:28:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nPS: Bruno, don't take my comments on this patch negatively.  It looks like an incredible debugging job that you did to find this problem in the first place.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "20b8174889d3d2b9bab9d81973e5900143bc8035",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 10:00:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nAFAIU, the patch fixes the issue as the decision on short niobuf is taken once?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "776764867cd9250b9e4555b78164d057f5c1d29d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 229,
        "name": "Bruno Faccini",
        "email": "bfaccini@nvidia.com",
        "username": "bfaccini"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 10:07:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nAndreas: No problem! Your comments are more than welcome to me because they always add value and force me to think in new directions.\nBTW, if I have written the patch this way, it is because I thought that the read/write concurency here was expected and the way to ensure read or write can cohabit was to read isize once, like already in osd_write_prep()",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "6cc2e07f34c349ae1f2218f40a03083a03fffa11",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 10:16:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sessions/a263d092-b1d6-11e4-bf90-5254006e85c2).  Ran 6 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "0edfeb179a2f2e29d0ab70ced9e76b7565056a09",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 229,
        "name": "Bruno Faccini",
        "email": "bfaccini@nvidia.com",
        "username": "bfaccini"
      },
      "date": "2015-02-11 10:19:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nAlso, and I am far to be a ZFS specialist and thus I may be easily wrong, but doing so is somewhat to replicate what happens on ZFS during concurrent read/write, is'nt-it ?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "365684d24d36435646ff3722e52ebf6b995bc8c6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
